Equi-marginal utility principle not expected
4.1.2.2 Imperfect information

Importance of information for decision making
Significance of asymmetric information
Imperfect information → difficulty making rational decisions → potential market failure
4.1.2.3 Aspects of behavioural economic theory

Bounded rationality and bounded self-control
Biases: rules of thumb, anchoring, availability and social norms
Importance of altruism and perceptions of fairness
4.1.2.4 Behavioural economics and economic policy

Choice architecture and framing
Nudges
Default choices, restricted choice and mandated choice
4.1.3 Price determination in a competitive market
4.1.3.1–4.1.3.6 (Same structure as AS 3.1.2, with additions:)

Under perfect competition, the supply curve is the marginal cost curve
Awareness of assumptions of the model of supply and demand
Competitive demand replaces "demand for substitute goods" in interrelationship between markets
4.1.4 Production, costs and revenue
4.1.4.1–4.1.4.2 (Same as AS: production/productivity, specialisation/division of labour)

4.1.4.3 The law of diminishing returns and returns to scale

Short run vs long run
Marginal, average and total returns
The law of diminishing returns
Returns to scale: increasing, constant, decreasing
Implications for costs of production
4.1.4.4 Costs of production

Fixed vs variable costs
Marginal, average and total costs
Short-run vs long-run costs
Reasons for shapes of marginal, average and total cost curves
Factor prices and productivity affect costs and choice of factor inputs
4.1.4.5 Economies and diseconomies of scale (As AS, plus:)

Relationship between returns to scale and economies/diseconomies of scale
L-shaped long-run average cost curve
Minimum efficient scale of production and its significance for industry structure and barriers to entry
4.1.4.6 Marginal, average and total revenue

Differences between marginal, average and total revenue
AR curve = firm's demand curve
Relationship between AR and MR
Relationship between MR and TR
4.1.4.7 Profit

Profit = TR − TC
Normal vs abnormal (supernormal) profit
Role of profit in a market economy
4.1.4.8 Technological change

Difference between invention and innovation
Effects on methods of production, productivity, efficiency, costs
Development of new products/markets; destruction of existing markets
Creative destruction
Influence on market structure
4.1.5 Perfect competition, imperfectly competitive markets and monopoly
4.1.5.1 Market structures

Spectrum from perfect competition to pure monopoly
Distinguished by: number of firms, product differentiation, ease of entry
4.1.5.2 The objectives of firms

Profit maximisation assumption in traditional theory
Profit-maximising rule: MC = MR
Divorce of ownership from control
Other objectives: survival, growth, quality, sales revenue maximisation, market share
Satisficing principle
4.1.5.3 Perfect competition

Formal diagrammatic analysis (short and long run)
Large numbers of producers, identical products, freedom of entry/exit, perfect knowledge
Firms are price takers
Given certain assumptions, perfect competition → efficient allocation of resources
4.1.5.4 Monopolistic competition

Formal diagrammatic analysis (short and long run)
Main characteristics
Non-price competition
4.1.5.5 Oligopoly

Main characteristics
Can differ in: number of firms, product differentiation, ease of entry
Defined by market structure or market conduct
Concentration ratios
Collusive vs non-collusive oligopoly; cooperation vs collusion
Kinked demand curve model (illustration of interdependence, not the only model)
Non-price competition, cartels, price leadership, price agreements, price wars, barriers to entry
Interdependence and uncertainty
Advantages and disadvantages
4.1.5.6 Monopoly and monopoly power

Formal diagrammatic analysis
Monopoly power influenced by: barriers to entry, competitors, advertising, product differentiation
Advantages and disadvantages
4.1.5.7 Price discrimination

Conditions necessary
Advantages and disadvantages
Diagrammatic analysis expected
4.1.5.8 The dynamics of competition and competitive market processes

Short-run and long-run benefits of competition
Competition beyond price
Creative destruction as a fundamental feature of market competition
4.1.5.9 Contestable and non-contestable markets

Market contestability and industry performance
Sunk costs and hit-and-run competition
4.1.5.10 Market structure, static efficiency, dynamic efficiency and resource allocation

Static vs dynamic efficiency
Productive efficiency: minimising ATC
Allocative efficiency: P = MC
Dynamic efficiency influenced by: R&D, investment in human/non-human capital, technological change
4.1.5.11 Consumer and producer surplus

Applied to: economic efficiency, welfare issues, price discrimination, dead-weight losses of monopoly
Diagrammatic analysis expected
4.1.6 The labour market
4.1.6.1 The demand for labour, marginal productivity theory

Derived demand
Marginal productivity theory of labour demand
Demand curve for labour: wage rate vs number employed
Shifts in demand curve; determinants of elasticity of demand for labour
4.1.6.2 Influences upon the supply of labour to different markets

Monetary and non-monetary considerations
Supply curve: wage rate vs number willing to work
Shifts in supply curve
Individual supply of labour / backward-bending supply curve not required
4.1.6.3 Perfectly competitive labour markets

Wage determination model
Market forces determine relative wage rates
4.1.6.4 Imperfectly competitive labour markets

Monopsony power, trade unions, imperfect information
Monopsony: employer uses market power to reduce wage rate and employment below competitive levels
Relevant diagrams expected
4.1.6.5 The influence of trade unions

Factors affecting ability to influence wages and employment
Impact in previously competitive vs monopsony labour markets
Relevant diagrams expected
4.1.6.6 The National Minimum Wage

Effects on labour markets
Advantages and disadvantages
4.1.6.7 Discrimination in the labour market

Conditions for wage discrimination
Impact of gender, ethnicity and other discrimination on wages, employment levels and types
4.1.7 The distribution of income and wealth: poverty and inequality
4.1.7.1 The distribution of income and wealth

Difference between income and wealth
Factors influencing distribution
Equality vs equity
Lorenz curve and Gini coefficient (interpret, not calculate)
Benefits and costs of more/less equal distributions
4.1.7.2 The problem of poverty

Relative vs absolute poverty
Causes and effects
4.1.7.3 Government policies to alleviate poverty and influence distribution

Available policies
Economic consequences
Evaluate approaches, recognising moral and political perspectives
4.1.8 The market mechanism, market failure and government intervention
4.1.8.1 How markets and prices allocate resources (As AS, plus:)

Advantages and disadvantages of the price mechanism
Extending price mechanism into new areas may be undesirable
4.1.8.2–4.1.8.3 (As AS, plus:)

Tragedy of the commons (relevant to environmental market failures)
4.1.8.4 Positive and negative externalities (As AS, but now using MSC/MSB diagrams:)

Absence of property rights leads to externalities
